{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:52.161Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining API endpoints**\n\nI've scoped down the task and I am now focused on defining the MVP user management API endpoints in Next.js, specifically under `/api/v1/users`. I'm excluding the landing page and GFF AI tools for now. The plan is to implement endpoints for listing, retrieving by ID, creating, updating, and patching status.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:53.591Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining API Routes**\n\nI'm now refining the API route structure. Based on existing Next.js API endpoints at `/app/api/v1/`, I'm going to create user management endpoints under `/app/api/v1/users`. Specifically, I'm working on the design for GET `/api/v1/users`. Access to these endpoints will be restricted to users with admin roles. I'm focusing on ensuring robust authentication and authorization.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:55.536Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying Endpoint Permissions**\n\nI'm now clarifying user role permissions for API endpoints. I will check the user's role in the token, which could be `\"gff_admin\"`, `\"client_admin\"`, or `\"client_member\"`. I'll allow `gff_admin` for all operations, and potentially `client_admin` for reads, but will keep it admin-only at first to KISS. I'm restricting creation and role changes to `gff_admin`. I'm starting to parse query parameters for filtering by `role`, `status`, and `client_id`, to get a list of users.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:57.073Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing User Filtering**\n\nI'm now implementing the user filtering functionality. I'm supporting filtering by `clientAssociation`, which is called `client` in `auth.ts`, either a partial or exact match. I'm also adding search capability to search by name or email. I will need to return user lists from the mock database, always excluding the `passwordHash` field.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:58.711Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Addressing Password Handling**\n\nI'm now focusing on password hashing for user creation and updates, making sure not to return `passwordHash`. I'm trying to ensure the existing `verifyUserPassword` function works correctly with the new hashing approach, and it seems that function already supports plaintext password fallback. I will need to update `verifyUserPassword` to handle the hashed password. I have to read the relevant code to verify assumptions.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:49:59.837Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Verifying Password Hashes**\n\nI've confirmed I can update `verifyUserPassword` to handle hashed passwords. My elegant solution ensures backward compatibility with plaintext passwords in the mock database by checking both the plaintext and the SHA-256 hash. This allows for seamless integration of the hashed passwords during user creation and updates, a robust and secure approach.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:50:01.992Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Centralizing Auth Logic**\n\nI'm now centralizing password hashing in `lib/api-auth.ts`, after confirming the chosen hashing function is robust. I'll include helper functions to get, add, update, and delete mock users. This will initialize the mock database on `global`. This ensures auth logic is fully centralized and correct. I'll read through the code again to verify assumptions, and ensure CRUD operations are supported.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:50:04.086Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Mock User Updates**\n\nI'm now refining the mock user update process. I'll need to support user lookup and updates by ID, not just email. I'll search the values of `API_MOCK_USERS` by ID. I will update the entry corresponding to the user's email if they change it. I'm focusing on ensuring data integrity when updating user information using the mock database, now that I have the correct logic.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:50:05.982Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing API Structure**\n\nI am now designing the API structure for User Admin CRUD APIs. I'm focusing on creating a narrative and visual metaphor, specifically around a cryptographically sealed state management system for data representation. I'm planning to describe security, roles, and password handling for secure user management. I will be sure to avoid any password exposure in responses. The plan is to create a clean and precise API structure.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
